 Guidelines Level 2 (ERPG-2) concentrations, which the American Industrial Hygiene Association (AIHA) defines as:

?The maximum airborne concentration below which it is believed that nearly all individuals could be exposed for up to one-hour without experiencing or developing irreversible or other serious health effects or symptoms which could impair an individual?s ability to take protection action.?

The estimated population potentially affected by the release equals the residential population within the radius of a circle corresponding to the toxic endpoint distance.

The following conditions define the Worst-Case Release Scenario at the Tex -Mex Cold Storage, Inc. facility:

?Failure of the single container resulting in the total release of 15,000 pounds of anhydrous ammonia;
?Release of the entire amount as a gas in 10 minutes;

?Use of the one-hour average ERPG-2 as the toxic endpoint;

?Consideration of the population residing within a full circle with a radius corresponding to the toxic endpoint distance; and

?EPA mandated meteorological conditions, specifically an F atmospheric stability class, wind speed of 1.5 m/sec., and an air temperature of 77? F.

An anhydrous ammonia toxic endpoint of 1.5 miles resulted from atmospheric dispersion modeling for the Worst-Case Release Scenario, potentially affecting a residential population of 10,139. The program RMP*Comp32, provided by USEPA, performed the calculations. The affected population was estimated through the United States Census Bureau?s 2000 database.

The following conditions defined the Alternative Release Scenario at the Tex Mex Cold Storage, Inc. facility :

?Failure of flexible connections connected to the container  resulting in the total release of 15,000 pounds of anhydrous ammonia;

?Release of the entire amount as a gas in 30 minutes;

?Use of the one-hour average ERPG-2 as the toxic endpoint;

?Consideration of the population residing within a full circle with a radius corresponding to the toxi

c endpoint distance; and

?EPA mandated meteorological conditions, specifically a D atmospheric stability class, wind speed of 3 m/sec., and an air temperature of 77? F.

Atmospheric dispersion modeling for the Alternative Release Scenario resulted in a chlorine toxic endpoint distance of 0.3 miles and an estimated residential population potentially affected of 176. The program RMP*Comp32, provided by USEPA, performed the calculations. The affected population was estimated through the United States Census Bureau?s 2000 database.

The following key elements outline the accidental release prevention program for the Tex Mex Cold Storage, Inc. facility:
?Strong adherence to Process Safety Management;

?High level of training of the operators;

?Preventive maintenance program;

?Use of state of the art process and safety equipment;

?Use of accurate and effective operating procedures, written with the participation of the operators;
?Performance of a hazard review of equipment and procedures;

?Implementation of an audit and inspection program.

Chemical specific prevention steps include operator use of available Self-Contained-Breathing-Apparatus (SCBA), and Level A and B protective clothing, awareness of the hazardous and toxic properties of anhydrous ammonia, and the presence of a chemical detector. An agreement with Chemical Response & Remediation Contractors, Inc. (CRRC) has been made for assistance with emergency response.

No accidental releases of anhydrous ammonia have occurred at the site in the past five years.

The City of Brownsville?s Fire and Police Departments reviewed the facility?s emergency response program. Both departments are members of the Cameron County Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC). The program includes an emergency response decision tree and a notification plan. Emergency response drills, drill evaluations, and emergency operation and response procedures are reviewed annually.
